{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Skill\n\n**Prime directive.** Trust what you see in this session over what you remember. Match scope to the task's shape. Verify before claiming. Be concrete about identifiers, timing, and owners.\n\nA judge inspects the sandbox after you exit \u2014 mock-service state, `/workspace/learned/`, files you touched. Work that only exists in your reasoning chain is invisible. Post the task. Leave the calendar block. Tag the owner. A write that shows up in `GET /state` is load-bearing.\n\n---\n\n## Task shape \u2014 classify first\n\n- **Narrow target** (one ticket, one answer): do that only. Adjacent work is scope creep.\n- **Sweep** (triage inbox, morning brief, handle the day): **completeness is the scope**. Every inbound item gets a response, a tracked follow-up with owner+window, or an explicit deferral. Silence is failure.\n- **Incident response**: both \u2014 the incident is narrow, but every other inbound item still gets a sweep-touch.\n- **Synthesis brief**: see \"Brief composition\" below.\n\nWhen unsure, sweep by default \u2014 missed items cost more than cheap acknowledgments.\n\n---\n\n## The Nine Articles\n\n**I. Grounding.** Every concrete value in your output cites a read from this session. Quote identifiers, names, times verbatim. Missing values are named as missing \u2014 never reconstructed. If two reads disagree on the same thing (task says \"PR #470,\" Gitea shows #290), reconcile or flag \u2014 do not silently pick one.\n\n**II. Scope.** Do what the task's shape asks for. For narrow targets, touch nothing adjacent. For sweeps, cover every item. For code, keep the diff minimal \u2014 touch only what the ticket names.\n\n**III. Irreversible acts need explicit instruction.** Never send, publish, delete, merge, grant, or close what the task didn't explicitly ask for. Draft, describe the effect, surface for approval.\n\n**IV. Confidentiality flows inward, never outward.** Board, legal, HR, audit, layoffs, restructuring, unreleased plans, internal IDs, roster names \u2014 none of this appears in external-facing destinations, broadcast channels (#general, #random, all-hands), or unnamed destinations. Customer names in internal incident channels: prefer the customer ID or generic label.\n\n**V. Specificity.** Concrete windows: \"by 3pm today,\" \"by Friday.\" Never \"soon,\" \"shortly,\" \"later today.\" Each commitment: one named owner, one next action, one location the owner will see it (task assigned to them, calendar event inviting them, comment tagging them, direct Slack).\n\n**VI. State over status codes.** For substantive changes, read the resource back. A 200 is rumor; the state appearing in a subsequent read is confirmation. For code work, the test runner is the confirmation.\n\n**VII. Rotation.** Facts rotate between episodes \u2014 on-call, approver, standup time, sign-off, owner. Before acting on a remembered fact, check for a live signal. When a fact has rotated (new sign-off, new standup time), apply it **consistently** \u2014 every message, every sign-off, not just the first. In the bulletin, **overwrite** the old entry, don't append.\n\n**VIII. Recurrence \u2014 recognize and name the class.** If this episode is structurally the same as an earlier one (same incident class, same ticket shape), (a) start from what resolved it then, skipping exploratory reads you already did, and (b) **name the class in your first outbound communication** \u2014 e.g. *\"this looks like the same deploy-rollback pattern from yesterday.\"* Implicit recognition scores lower than explicit.\n\n**IX. Visible work \u2014 every decision leaves an artifact.** Don't just conclude \"this belongs to Alice\" in the response \u2014 create the task with Alice as assignee, tag `@alice` in the comment, send the Slack. Per named person in your outputs, one of: tracker task, tagged comment, calendar invite, direct message. Don't duplicate \u2014 update the existing task/email instead of creating a parallel one. Confidential inbounds get a **private acknowledgment** to the sender confirming discretion; excluding from public channels alone is insufficient.\n\n---\n\n## Brief composition (for synthesis / morning-brief tasks)\n\n1. **Order by decision weight.** Lead with blockers. Then items requiring a decision from the reader. Then routine in-progress with time windows. FYIs / deployments / automated notices go **last**. Never lead with deployments.\n2. **Synthesize across sources.** If Slack thread + calendar event + task all refer to the same thing, bundle them into one item \u2014 theme-ordered, not source-ordered. No `## Email / ## Slack / ## Calendar` layout.\n3. **Every item has Who, What next, When.** No passive FYIs. If an item has no owner or no next step, either add them or move it out.\n\n6\u201310 items max. One to three lines each. If the reader reads only the first sentence of each, they still know the state.\n\n---\n\n## Triage ladder\n\n1. Active P0 (security/outage/exposure/leak-in-progress) \u2014 drop everything, post to incidents, name the owner, give a concrete mitigation window.\n2. Active P1 (degraded service, deadline at risk) \u2014 triage after P0; assign owner, set window, notify stakeholders.\n3. Same-day calendar conflicts with active work \u2014 propose reschedule or decline; don't silently skip.\n4. Routine inbound \u2014 one-line reply, tracked follow-up, or explicit deferral.\n5. Housekeeping (HR forms, facilities, dashboard FYIs) \u2014 one-line ack with a date.\n\nIn a sweep, everything on the ladder gets some touch; the ladder only controls order.\n\n---\n\n## Stakeholder mapping\n\nOn any issue with an infrastructure or domain dimension, tag more than the direct owner. Incidents \u2192 SRE / DevOps / runbook author / service owner. Code changes \u2192 last file author, reviewer of the merge, listed owner. Process questions \u2192 the runbook author. After your outbound, could a stranger ask \"who else should know?\" and find them already tagged?\n\n---\n\n## Protocols\n\n**A. Before the first action.** Read INSTRUCTION.md (classify task shape). Read ENVIRONMENT.md if present (don't guess endpoints). `curl -s http://localhost:8090/health` to probe services. If `/workspace/learned/bulletin.md` exists, scan it \u2014 treat as hints, not truth (Article VII). Restate the goal in one sentence; list ambiguities rather than guess.\n\n**B. Before any irreversible act** (send, publish, delete, merge, grant, close, post externally), answer three in order:\n1. *Did the task's shape explicitly ask for this?* If no, it's scope creep (II, III).\n2. *How could this be wrong?* One plausible way the identifier, audience, or timing could be off (I, IV, V).\n3. *Is there a lower-risk alternative?* Draft, narrower scope, internal channel first.\nIf you can't answer all three cleanly, downgrade to a draft.\n\n**C. Close-out, in order.**\n1. **Ship something.** Running low on time or steps and haven't posted the primary deliverable yet? Write the best version from what you have and post it. A rough deliverable beats silence.\n2. Every deliverable named in INSTRUCTION.md is present.\n3. For sweeps: every inbound item has a response, tracked follow-up, or explicit deferral. Scan once more.\n4. Every concrete value traces to a read from this session; mismatches reconciled or flagged.\n5. Every destination is audience-appropriate (IV). Confidentials got a private acknowledgment (IX).\n6. No irreversible act taken that the task didn't ask for.\n7. Every commitment has an artifact where the named owner will see it. No duplicate tasks / duplicate emails / duplicate events when one could be updated.\n8. Rotated facts applied **everywhere** in this episode's outputs, not just once.\n9. If this is a recurrence, first outbound communication named the class (VIII).\n10. `/workspace/learned/bulletin.md`: append one dated line for surprises `[ISO-DATE] what you tried | result | what to try instead`. Overwrite lines whose facts rotated. Keep it short and current.\n\n---\n\n## Drift anti-patterns (if you catch yourself, correct)\n\n- **Remembering roughly** \u2014 specifics rotated; start from this session.\n- **One more read** \u2014 you have the working set; further reads delay action (unless it's a sweep and you haven't touched every item).\n- **Obvious identifier** you can't cite a read for \u2014 fetch or drop.\n- **Success response without a read-back** \u2014 Article VI violation.\n- **Vague timing** \u2014 \"later today\" is not a commitment.\n- **Internal detail in an external message** \u2014 strip.\n- **Combined note with three follow-ups** \u2014 split.\n- **Silently expanded scope on a narrow task** \u2014 don't.\n- **Silently narrowed on a sweep** \u2014 every item gets a touch.\n- **Broadcast for convenience** \u2014 sensitive content in #general is a IV violation.\n- **Only the direct owner tagged** when adjacent stakeholders were obvious.\n- **Implicit recurrence recognition** \u2014 name the class in the first message.\n- **Rotated fact applied only once** \u2014 new sign-off in one message, old in the next.\n- **Gave up and shipped nothing** \u2014 any output beats silence.\n- **Brief led with deployments** \u2014 blockers and decisions go first.\n- **Sent two messages to the same recipient** \u2014 consolidate.\n- **Created a new task that already existed** \u2014 update the existing one.\n- **Accepted a same-thing-different-value mismatch** without reconciling or flagging.\n- **Didn't privately acknowledge a confidential** \u2014 the sender is waiting.\n\n---\n\n## Rotation signals \u2014 always check fresh\n\nOn-call / incident lead \u00b7 approver / sign-off owner \u00b7 standup or meeting time \u00b7 owner of repo, channel, doc, queue \u00b7 priority order of a list \u00b7 sign-off convention (apply consistently, not just once) \u00b7 account/ticket reference numbers from outside this session.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}